{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630579"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:17:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:17:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17321"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17321"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.14,0.14,0.09,0.59]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10011"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70056"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10011"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55518"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10023"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23506"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70056"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brown colour of faeces is due to the presence of specific end-products of haem metabolism. One of these products is stercobolin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the formation of stercobilin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct reduction of bilirubin in the liver","Oxidation of biliverdin in the spleen","Breakdown of haemoglobin in macrophages","Conjugation of bilirubin in hepatocytes","Bacterial metabolism of urobilinogen in the intestine"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial metabolism of urobilinogen in the intestine\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for producing stercobilin. When conjugated bilirubin reaches the intestine, it is first converted to urobilinogen by gut bacteria. Some urobilinogen enters the enterohepatic circulation, while the remainder is further metabolised by intestinal bacteria to form stercobilin, which gives faeces its characteristic brown colour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect reduction of bilirubin in the liver\u003C/strong\u003E - The liver conjugates bilirubin but does not produce stercobilin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxidation of biliverdin in the spleen\u003C/strong\u003E - Biliverdin is reduced to bilirubin, not oxidised to stercobilin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjugation of bilirubin in hepatocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - This process produces conjugated bilirubin, not stercobilin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreakdown of haemoglobin in macrophages\u003C/strong\u003E - This produces biliverdin which is then converted to bilirubin, not directly to stercobilin\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this pathway is important as changes in stercobilin production can result in alterations in stool colour, which may indicate underlying pathology in the biliary system or intestinal flora.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Stercobilin is produced when intestinal bacteria metabolise urobilinogen, giving faeces its brown colour.","Urobilinogen is formed when bilirubin is reduced by gut bacteria in the intestine."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55518"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17321"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55518"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T09:10:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T09:11:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10011"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70056"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"